HWUSD will offer online learning for at least the first quarter for the 20-21 school year. All students will be assigned IPADS and the school will provide hotspots to support connectivity. Details on distribution will be posted at a later date. School will begin on Tuesday, September 8, 2020.

Registration packets are being sent out through mail to households which contain the school calendar, IPAD agreements, etc. Completed packets should be mailed back using the return stamped envelope or can be dropped of at the K8 and HS offices. We encourage you to return your registration forms ASAP.
Our district appreciates your patience and support. We want to assure you we are working to provide a high quality virtual learning experience while keeping our student, staff and community safety as our top priority. If you have any questions please contact Mr. Jeff Gregorich or Mrs. Pamela Gonzalez. Thank you!

Arizona Youth Partnership
July 20 at 8:12 PM ·

Free Online Summer Program for youth! July 27-August 6th.

In prevention with Pima Prevention Partnership, a trained Pathways coach will deliver the program to up to 20 youth. Youth will receive training in first aid, learn about healthy relationships, develop a career plan and participate in a service learning project. Money Habitudes, a financial literacy curriculum will help youth evaluate their beliefs and opinions about money, and learn budgeting skills. All participants in the program will receive First Aid/CPR certification and receive $75.00 upon completion of the program toward work/education supplies.

Register at http://ow.ly/SCej50ADnwG

post_text:
Our school and staff send our sincere condolences to the family of Mr. Peter Guzman. He was an educator who had a lasting impact on all who he taught, worked with and coached. Mr. Guzman had a long career in education and made a difference in the copper cooridor communities. He was a Hayden High School alumni and a Lobo at heart. He was proud of the small mining town from where he was raised and started his career.
We had the honor of having him speak at our last career fair and at last year’s graduation. His message included the pride he felt in giving back to his school and community, the belief in our students potential for success, and the importance of forever holding pride and traditions instilled in us at Hayden.
Mr. Guzman you will forever be remembered and appreciated by your Lobo family. Rest in Peace❤️

post_text: Great news for our students, school and community!
shared_text:
Roy Sandoval is with Jacque Cline Sanders.
May 26 at 6:01 PM ·

Today Jacque Sanders and I were pleased to present for the Gila County Board of Supervisors approval, an award for the Gila County Information Technology Consortium for $19,817,940.06 (yes MILLION!) to bring high speed internet cabling to schools and libraries in the County. The upshot is, this cabling will be a benefit to each community in the County as well. It has been a long two and a half year quest with starts, stops, uncertainty, questions etc. However, many people gave us advice and support along the way. WE DID IT! Taking just a little time to celebrate before the construction starts.

post_text: Ms. Angela Skillings Happy Teacher Appreciation Week! post_text: In honor of teacher appreciation week we want to acknowledge our awesome teaching staff! Introducing Mrs. Bethany Chavez. Mrs. Chavez earned a BA in Special Education in 2016, and a M.Ed in Instructional Design in 2018, both from Western Governors University. She is currently studying to earn her Ed.D in Curriculum & Teaching at Northcentral University. This year wraps up her fourth year of teaching. She taught special education in Oklahoma for two years and has spent the last two years teaching Kindergarten at Leonor-Hambly K8. “I miss my kindergarten students very much! I hope you are all doing well, staying healthy, and continuing to learn at home!”

post_text: The Hayden -Winkelman school district will be extending its Spring Break for an additional week beginning Monday, March 16, 2020. At this time we have no known cases of students or staff with the Coronavirus however the safety of our students and staff is top priority. This decision is a precaution and will give us an opportunity to see what continues to unfold with the spread of the Coronavirus and the development of more tests. Although we are part of the first schools in Arizona to close due to this virus other states across the country and higher education in our state have taken similar precautions. The district will continue updates via the HWUSD website and social media.
